deck: Joseph Greene was a writer best known for creating Tom Corbett, Space Cadet. He also ghost wrote many DC, Fawcett and other comics during the Golden and early Silver Ages.
description:
During the Golden Age, it was common for writers to not use their real name in case the author moved on to other media. Thus, Greene wrote under many pseudonyms, including Joe Green, Joseph Lawrence, Joseph Verdy, Larry Verdi and Lawrence Vert.

While he is most famous for Tom Corbett, Space Cadet, he also contributed to many of DC Comics' signature works during the early 1940s, including Action Comics, Detective Comics, All-American Comics and Green Lantern.
name: Joseph Greene

deck: Artist and writer, worked on the Eisner and Harvey-nominated web-comic The Guns of Shadow Valley.
description:
Dave Wachter is an American comic artist who graduated at the School of the Art Institute of Chicago.

He began his career in 2004 when he and writer Jim Clark teamed up for their critically acclaimed self published series Scar Tissue. Following that success, they once again collaborated on the epic Western web-comic The Guns of Shadow Valley, which was nominated for an Eisner Award for Best Digital Comic and a Harvey Award for Best Online Work. To finish this comic and publish it as a hardcover graphic novel, The Guns of Shadow Valley is now a Kickstarter project.
name: Dave Wachter

deck: Italian artist, friend of Hugo Pratt.
description:
Born in Venice in 1923, Battaglia entered into his comic career in 1946, co-founding and producing work for the Italian magazine, Asso di Picche. Here, he worked with other notable figures in European comics, among them Hugo Pratt, creator of Corto Maltese. In the 1960s, Battaglia illustrated a series of adaptations of fairy tales and classic stories and novels for Corriere dei Piccoli and Corriere dei Ragazzi, both publications of which also employed other legends such as Sergio Toppi, Ferdinando Tacconi, and Attilio Micheluzzi, among others.

Battaglia is noted for his distinctive and expressive, yet very classically influenced style. Like Sergio Toppi and many other Italians, he really pushed for experimental and striking page layout and panel design, and is among Italy's most retroactively celebrated and respected comic masters. Battaglia passed away unexpectedly in 1983.
name: Dino Battaglia

deck: Russell Stamm was the sole creator and artist for Invisible Scarlet O'Neil, after having worked on Tiny Tim and Dick Tracy comics. Invisible Scarlet is one of the first heroines in comics, and probably the first superpowered heroine.
description:
Career

Stanley Link, the creator of the comic strip Tiny Tim, was Stamm's uncle. He noted the boy's interest in illustration and introduced him to Sidney Smith (The Gumps creator). Stamm's career began in 1934, when he worked in the art department of the Chicago Tribune, as an assistant to Link. A year later, he earn a position assisting Chester Gould on the Dick Tracy strip.

Stamm married and moved with his wife Marjorie to Oak Park, IL in 1939. At this point, he decided to stop assisting on other strips, and develop his own. It's not known exactly how he came up with his concept for a superpowered heroine. Though he'd worked on Dick Tracy for years and no stranger to violence in strips, his heroine, Invisible Scarlet O'Neil, was not violent, but a mild-mannered heroine (who didn't even have an alter-ego) who helped children and people in need.

Stamm was drafted into the Army in 1944. PFC Stamm served 17 months as a photo retouch artist. He worked on illustrations for training films and designed a poster which was nationally displayed for the Helicopter Division. His last 3 months in the service were spent as art editor and director of the Army Air Force newspaper.

World War II changed things, but Stamm tried to adapt Invisible Scarlet to suit this new world's tastes. Popularity in superpowered characters was waning, and people were discovering television. The idea that comic strips led to juvenile delinquency forced some publishers out of business. In 1948, a new character, Stainless Steel, was introduced to the strip. In 1955, due to Steel's popularity, the strip was renamed "Stainless Steel." This popularity caused a jump in syndication, and Stamm had to hire an assistant, Emery Clarke, to help with the strips.

Tired of conflicts with editors, he asked to be released from his contract with Field Enterprises and the strip ended in 1956.

Russell Stamm Productions was his next venture, a Chicago firm that created storyboards and animation for commercials, embracing television as a medium. His were some of the first designs for the Jolly Green Giant, Charlie the Tuna and the Hostess Cup Cake Twins. His advertising work earned him several national awards.

Personal Life

Russell Stamm was the youngest of 7 children, born in Chicago, IL on April 16th, 1915. He married Marjorie Dingham on April 22, 1939. The couple had two children, William Paul Stamm (November 1942) and Russell Jr. (February 1946). He died of a heart attack on August 2, 1969. He was buried in Concordia Cemetery, in Forest Park, IL.
name: Russell Stamm
